# Stack
- Using NextJS, version 16 with ReactJS, version 19, to build the web app
- Use React Context to manage states
- Use Next Intl (i18n) to internationalization (en, pt-BR)
- Use Tailwind CSS to style
- Use Yup and Zod to forms
- Use Mui/icons-material and Mui/material to icons, svg and others
- Use reown as wallet connection (web3 plug-in-play)

## Code
- Should be responsible, thinking in mobile-first
- Use FSD Architecture to organize the code
- Prefer Component Composition 
- Prefer SSR instead
- Use Cache to increase perfomance
- Prefer divide UI/UX from business rules, using techniques like Pattern Container/Presentational.
- Always think about maintainability and scale of the project during development

## General
- Implement using Clean code concepts
- Implement using SOLID principle
- Write code and comments only in English, even when the prompt was written in other language
- Always verify that the code is compiling correctly at the end of your changes.
- Always refactor the code to increase quality, using industry best practices at the end of your changes.
- Always think about internalization, cause must be access globaly.

# FSD Architecture Summary

## Layers (Hierarchy: Top \rightarrow$ Bottom)
- App (src/app/): Initialization, routes, global providers, and styles. No business logic.
- Pages (src/pages/): Page composition. Contains page UI and specific dialogs. No fetch or complex logic.
- Widgets (src/widgets/): Complex and independent components that combine multiple Features.
- Features (src/features/): Interactions that generate value (e.g., "Like", "Checkout"). Contains API, UI, library (logic), and model.
- Entities (src/entities/): Domain models (User, Product). Contains interfaces, enums, constants, and formatters.
- Shared (src/shared/): UI Kit (Button, Input), generic utilities, infrastructure configuration (Axios, Prisma). Business independent.

## Core Rules
- Linear Hierarchy: A layer can only import from layers below it (e.g., Feature imports from Entity, but Entity never imports from Feature).
- Slices: Division by business domain within the layers (e.g., entities/user, features/auth).
- Segments: Technical division within the Slice (ui, api, model, lib, config).
- Public API: Every slice/segment must have an index.ts file. Only what is exported there can be used externally.
- Don't Repeat Yourself (DRY): Domain Interfaces and Enums reside in Entities; never duplicate types or use magic strings.